West 124th Street, west from Amsterdam Avenue to Broadway. Seen across buildings at the latter point in the International House of Columbia University on Riverside Drive. Views 1 and 2 are extensive and show prominently the south and north sides respectively; 3 & 4 being similarly represented from a point nearer Broadway. Note in the latter two views the I.R.T. subway system emerging to become an elevated line.

W. 124th Street, east from Amsterdam Avenue and across same. View No. 2 shows mainly the south side and upon which stands 15 five story tenement houses owned by John D. Rockefeller Jr. These, consisting of Nos. 432 to 400 W. 124th Street, are the be demolished according to the New York Times of October 5, 1938. No plans for the future use of this site have yet been announced. Backing up to this row is the rear of the Lincoln School of Teachers College on 123rd Street.

August 1930
View 2: August 24, 1938.

West 124th Street, east from Amsterdam Avenue. At the left, at Morningside Avenue, is a clearance upon which stood until recently, the buildings owned by John D. Rockefeller. To their rears abutted the rear of the Lincoln School of Teachers College. This is now open to view. The institutional structure in the center background is Sydenham Hospital.
